{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526000"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14107"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14107"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.18,0.12,0.51,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51670"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6777"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14107"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36968"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"1659"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"3493"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43488"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51670"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of severe pain and swelling in his right big toe. He underwent a renal transplant two years ago for end-stage kidney disease secondary to polycystic kidney disease. His medical history includes hypertension and dyslipidaemia. On examination, his right first metatarsophalangeal joint is swollen, erythematous, and exquisitely tender to touch. The patient is commenced on a xanthine oxidase inhibitor.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following immunosuppressive medications used in renal transplantation may cause a potentially serious interaction with this newly commenced medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tacrolimus","Cyclosporin","Mycophenolate","Azathioprine","Everolimus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario is presenting with symptoms typical of acute gout, a common complication in renal transplant recipients. The treatment initiated, a xanthine oxidase inhibitor (likely allopurinol), is standard therapy for gout. However, in transplant patients, medication interactions are a critical consideration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAzathioprine\u003C/strong\u003E is the immunosuppressive medication that can cause a potentially serious interaction with allopurinol. Inhibition of xanthine oxidase by allopurinol decreases the rate of conversion of azathioprine and mercaptopurine to inactive metabolites. The subsequent increased plasma concentrations of the active metabolites may lead to life-threatening myelosuppression, which increases the risk of infections in already immunosuppressed renal transplant patients. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETacrolimus \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Ecyclosporin\u003C/strong\u003E (calcineurin inhibitors), while crucial immunosuppressant medications in renal transplantation, do not have significant interactions with allopurinol. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMycophenolate\u003C/strong\u003E (anti-metabolite) does not interact significantly with allopurinol. It is commonly used in combination with calcineurin inhibitors and prednisolone in standard renal transplant immunosuppression regimens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEverolimus\u003C/strong\u003E, an mTOR inhibitor, also does not have a clinically significant interaction with allopurinol. However, like other immunosuppressants, it requires careful monitoring and dose adjustment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing gout in transplant patients, it is crucial to consider not only the immediate treatment of the acute attack but also the long-term management and potential drug interactions. If a patient is on azathioprine and requires allopurinol, careful monitoring and dose adjustment or alternative treatments should be considered. This case highlights the complexity of managing comorbidities in transplant patients and the importance of awareness of drug interactions in this cohort.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Allopurinol, a xanthine oxidase inhibitor, can interact dangerously with azathioprine, potentially leading to severe myelosuppression."],"references":["Allopurinol \u2013 Life-threatening interaction with azathioprine or mercaptopurine [Internet]. www.medsafe.govt.nz. Available from: https://www.medsafe.govt.nz/profs/PUArticles/September2020/Allopurinol-life-threatening-interaction-azathioprine-mercaptopurine.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36968"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14107"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36968"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-27T18:27:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-27T18:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6777"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51670"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"crea